        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(infra): preserve inherited gateway PID across reparent during cleanup",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n`cleanStaleGatewayProcessesSync` already excludes the caller and its ancestor chain from kill candidates (#68451). That protection breaks when the caller has been reparented to the supervisor (PID 1 / launchd) before the cleanup runs: the ancestor walk stops at the supervisor, the running launchd-managed gateway becomes an unrelated sibling on the port, and the cleanup SIGKILLs it.\n\nThis change captures `OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_SERVICE_PID` from inherited env before the gateway-cli overwrites it with its own PID, then threads the captured value through into the exclusion set so the launchd-managed parent is kept out of the kill list even across a reparent boundary.\n\nThe protection is opt-in per call site. `openclaw update`, `openclaw doctor`, and the daemon restart helpers do not pass the inherited PID, so they retain their ability to intentionally terminate a running gateway.\n\n## Real-world reproduction\n\nA user `~/.zshrc` containing this legacy pre-launchd auto-start block:\n\n```bash\nif ! pgrep -x \"openclaw-gateway\" > /dev/null; then\n  (openclaw gateway >/dev/null 2>&1 &)\nfi\n```\n\ncombined with codex 0.135.0 spawning `/bin/zsh -c \"set -e; . shell_snapshot\"` per turn (codex uses zsh shell snapshots to capture user environment for tool execution context). Each turn:\n\n1. Gateway A receives a chat request, spawns codex.\n2. Codex spawns the per-turn shell snapshot. zsh sources `~/.zshrc`, hits the legacy block, the `pgrep -x openclaw-gateway` does not match A's process title in time (zsh subshell timing), and the subshell starts a new `openclaw gateway` B in background.\n3. The subshell exits; B is reparented to launchd.\n4. B enters `runGatewayCommand`. `process.env[OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_SERVICE_PID]` still holds A's PID (inherited from gateway A through codex through zsh), but is immediately overwritten with B's own PID.\n5. B calls `cleanStaleGatewayProcessesSync`. Ancestor walk sees `process.ppid === 1` (launchd) and stops there. A appears on lsof for the port as an unrelated PID. B SIGKILLs A.\n6. launchd `KeepAlive: { Crashed: true }` respawns A. Cycle repeats on the next chat request.\n\nA forensic launchd unified-log tracker on the affected host captured 33 such kill events between 2026-05-30 and 2026-06-05, each `gateway [PID] exited due to SIGKILL | sent by node[PID]` with the killer always being a new openclaw gateway instance whose env carried `OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_SERVICE_PID` matching the victim. Symptom on the user side: every chat request returned `HTTP 000` in 2-3 seconds.\n\nThe host-side fix was deleting the legacy zshrc block, but the openclaw cleanup primitive should not be reachable into a suicide-kill state via that path in the first place.\n\n## Verification\n\n```\n$ node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/infra/restart-stale-pids.test.ts\n Test Files  1 passed (1)\n      Tests  52 passed | 2 skipped (54)\n\n$ node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/cli/gateway-cli/run.option-collisions.test.ts src/cli/update-cli.test.ts\n Test Files  2 passed (2)\n      Tests  150 passed (150)\n\n$ pnpm tsgo --noEmit -p tsconfig.json\n(clean)\n```\n\nThe two new tests in `src/infra/restart-stale-pids.test.ts`:\n\n- `excludes the inherited gateway service PID when the caller has been reparented to launchd` stubs `process.ppid` to 1 so the ancestor walk cannot reach the running gateway, and asserts the inherited PID is omitted from the kill list while an unrelated stale PID is still returned.\n- `ignores a non-positive inherited gateway PID rather than poisoning the kill list` documents the undefined/0/negative input contract so a future refactor cannot silently start excluding pid 0.\n\nExisting #68451 ancestor-exclusion tests still pass and continue to cover the non-reparent path.\n\n## Out of scope\n\n- The legacy auto-start block in user `~/.zshrc` is host config; not addressed here.\n- No `openclaw update` / `openclaw doctor` behavior changes. Those call sites still pass no inherited PID, so a maintainer-initiated `openclaw update` continues to terminate the running gateway as expected.\n- Windows code path also accepts the new parameter but the suicide-kill scenario this fixes is shell-driven and Unix-only; the Windows path keeps API symmetry but the behavioral change is dormant there.\n",
        "branch": "fix/stale-pid-cleanup-reparent-protection",
